Every year, the committee decides on new drugs that will be given to the public free of charge through the HMOs  but a new report by the State Comptroller published Tuesday warns that the company has been operating for more than 20 years without control reports on its activities and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council supervising and examining its activities and examining it.
Israel Hayom correspondent Ran Reznik adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted following the ongoing revelations in Israel Hayom about the failures of the basket of drugs.
According to Matanyahu Engelman's report, he recommends "in the process of expanding the basket, make corrections and improvements, which will lead to a better utilization of the health services basket budget that the public is entitled to".
Throughout the years of the existence of the mechanism for adding drugs to the basket, in 2021-1998, eight billion shekels were added to the state budget  with the addition fluctuating annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels  with the addition fluctuating annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels  between 0 and 500 million shekels  with the addition fluctuating annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels  each year.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add about 800 new drugs and technologies to the healthcare basket, at a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In practice, the budget allocated to expand the basket was smaller than the volume of requests.
In most of the Committee's years of operation ( 90% of the time), the amount of budgetary increment was less than 1 per cent. 5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired supplement rate.
The auditor notes that it is necessary to examine and regulate the height of the annual supplement in order to enable certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that "the transparency model in the basket work is flawed"
Thus, for example, the procedure for the work of the Basket Committee states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 160- 109 days, when sometimes the minutes of the final meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in publishing the protocols undermines the transparency of the decisions; due to this, the ability of the bidders  patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies  to submit repeated requests as soon as possible and relevant may be impaired, after they have learned lessons from the rejection of their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and amended their proposals, and reassessed the feasibility of receiving them in the next round, " the auditor noted in the report, "The comptroller noted in the report, "The comptroller noted.
“ The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules set out in the procedure.”
Out of thousands of submissions, only one economic comment was submitted.
Another criticism of Engelman concerns a preliminary process of evaluating the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The auditor found that about half ( 46%) of the submitted technologies did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the rejection.
Another flaw concerns the activities of the subcommittee of the basket of drugs, which is closed to the media and the public, and in which patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The auditor recommends adding a public representative or examining the possibility of publishing the discussions to the public without confidential commercial details.
The procedure according to which the Health Services Basket Committee operates states that "an economic assessment must be submitted" to a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic assessment has been submitted out of thousands of submissions  and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, requests were submitted to the Basket Committee for 2019-2021 to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report found that the requests were not accompanied by economic assessments, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved due to reducing the damage caused by obesity-related diseases or due to the ability to avoid stomach shortening surgery.
It also emerges that the decisions of the Medicines Basket Committee are inconsistent with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparations for treating the growth of chronic diseases as goals, but in the framework of the decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The auditor also warns that since 2011, services that are not the responsibility of the HMOs have also been included, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, provided by the Ministry of Health ( the “ Third Addendum”) .
This, when the legal framework for this step is regulated only retrospectively.
In the past six years, NIS 74 million of the addition to the basket of medicines has been used for these services.
Engelman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the procedures for the work of the basket and also determine whether a separate financial supplement is needed for these services.
About a third of the new drugs that enter the drug basket are defined as “ drugs at no added cost,” the use of which does not cost the health funds an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The auditor suggests examining the possibility that these drugs will be discussed in a different and shortened track, so that the basket of drugs can be updated several times a year and not just once a year.
There is no supervision of the use of particularly expensive drugs.
The audit also shows that since the basket committee's work began 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds to report and has not supervised the scope of uses and utilization of the drugs in the basket, information that could have allowed the Ministry to analyze and control the budget given to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports relating to the years 2009-2006 have been published, and these have also been published considerably late ( the last one was published this year and dealt with the utilization of the budget in 2007-2009) .
“ The delay in conducting tests may lead to difficulty in collecting and analyzing the data, irrelevance of the conclusions arising from the test after such a long period of time, subcommittee suboptimal pricing, and decision-making based on non-final findings,” the report said.
In addition, the Ministry also does not audit and supervise the use of particularly expensive drugs and has not conducted lessons learned from them.
These are 10 drugs that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket( 1) . NIS 7 billion in 2016-2021)) .
For this, the critic wrote: “ It is recommended that the Ministry of Health carry out individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the extent of their use compared to the estimates.
Controls and analysis will make it possible to draw systemic conclusions about the work process of the Basket Committee and the Subcommittee, and about how the estimates are prepared when pricing drugs and technologies and improve them.
