Medical malpractice in the different stages of childbirth
In order to receive compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that the damage was caused by that negligence.
Childbirth is one of the most joyful and exciting events in the life of a family.
Unfortunately, however, births sometimes end in serious damage to the mother or newborn as a result of the negligence of the medical staff.
In cases where the birth ended in physical injury to the newborn or the mother, there is room to examine the chain of events that led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in the field of medical malpractice will examine whether there were defects in the conduct of the medical staff during the various stages of birth that caused the damage and, as he deems appropriate, will consult a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every error in treatment on the part of the medical staff amounts to negligence ( in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that its management was negligent.
When then is it negligence?
When the doctor's error was due to incompetence or deviation from the reasonable level of caution, and incompetence and deviation from the accepted level of caution caused harm to the patient that would not have been caused if the doctor had not acted in this way.
In this article we will examine the different stages of childbirth, explain what complications may occur at each stage and when they arise to medical malpractice.
The contraction phase is contracted.
The contraction phase lasts an average of 8 to 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix opens gradually ( in order to allow the passage of the fetus during birth) and at the end of the process should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most cases of medical malpractice during labor involve failure to identify fetal distress prior to birth, which caused damage to the newborn, sometimes even manifested by cerebral palsy.
Cerebral Palsy ( CP) :
Cerebral palsy may be caused by a failure to identify or delay in identifying perinatal asphyxia, which manifests itself in a failure to supply oxygen to the brain tissue of the fetus.
In general, monitoring the mother's condition and correct interpretation of the monitor that monitors fetal heart activity should lead to early identification of the development of fetal distress, which allows the medical team to act quickly and extract the newborn before it is irreversibly damaged.
Cases in which the medical staff ignores signs indicating that the fetus is suffering from a lack of oxygen or that the staff does not correctly interpret the data on its face and in particular the fetal monitor or responds late to the distress expressed by the monitor  may constitute negligence.
Cerebral palsy may also be caused by umbilical cord prolapse and uterine rupture that was not detected in time.
Even in these difficult events, it is worth clarifying whether the medical staff acted properly.
For example, attorney Anna Reif Lignese, of Caspi Srour & Co., a law firm specializing in representing victims of medical malpractice, says that her firm handled a claim of a child injured during his birth after the midwife ruptured the amniotic sac when the fetal head was too high, thus leading to umbilical cord prolapse ( when the umbilical cord precedes the fetal head) and impaired oxygen supply to the fetal brain ( as a result of pressure of the fetal head on the umbilical cord) and being born with injury to the fetal head) and being born with injury to the fetal head and being born with injury to the fetal head) and being born with injury to the fetal brain ( as a result of pressure on the fetal head on the umbilical cord) and being born with injury to the fet
In another case, the lawyer said that her office filed a lawsuit due to severe medical negligence by the staff of the maternity ward at a large hospital, which during the birth did not identify clear signs at the time that required a real suspicion that the mother was suffering from a rupture of the uterus in the surgical scar area of her previous pregnancy.
The fetus that was ejected through the rupture of its mother's womb into the abdominal cavity suffered severe fetal distress until it was rescued at a late stage when it was on the verge of death.
Due to the severe fetal suffering during his birth, the child suffered a complex neurological disability.
We emphasize that in order to receive compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal link between the negligence of the medical staff that led to the failure to identify the asphyxiation and the damage caused to the newborn child, that is, that the damage was caused due to said negligence and not for any other reason or cause.
Examination of the causal relationship will be carried out through the examination of medical indicators that, according to the medical literature, only in their existence there is a causal relationship between the asphyxiation and the brain injury.
Among other things, the indicators of the level of acidity in the fetus's blood, its Apgar scores, the existence of neurological and systemic damage and more are examined.
The death of the fetus.
The active birth stage is active.
The stage of active birth begins when the opening of the cervix reaches a diameter of 10 cm and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical stage.
Delay in childbirth and avoidance of caesarean section.
In some cases, dysfunctional birth develops, i.e., lack of progression of the active birth process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a caesarean section, in order to prevent various damages that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay in birth.
“ There are cases in which failure to perform a caesarean section in a timely manner can cause irreversible damage to the fetus,” attorney Reif-Lignese explained to us,” she explained to us.
"For example, we conducted a medical malpractice lawsuit for the death of a newborn child caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section.
Contrary to any known medical practice, the medical staff were not educated to identify the fetal distress and perform a caesarean section despite the particularly slow progress of childbirth.
The delay in performing the operation caused extensive systemic damage to the birth which finally led to her death shortly after her birth."
Negligence in vacuum birth.
In situations where the mother or fetus is in significant danger that requires a particularly rapid termination of the birth, a vacuum birth ( empty tube) is sometimes performed.
In this process, a "cap" is attached to the fetus' head using a vacuum and the fetus is forcefully pulled out by force.
Naturally, this operation involves dangers and may cause damage to both the fetus and the mother and therefore requires great care, precision and skill, which requires great care, precision and skill.
In these cases, medical malpractice may manifest itself in the fact that the doctor does not adhere to the mandatory guidelines and performs the operation despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the fetal head is too high in the pelvis, or performs it for longer than permitted or when, despite the failure of a large number of attempts, the doctor continues and repeats the operation more than the number of attempts allowed.
In these cases, if the negligent vacuum operation caused damage to the newborn  among other things, it could cause cranial damage and bleeding that could cause the development of brain damage  there is room for filing a tort claim.
Paralysis named after ERB.
Paralysis named after Erb, here is a congenital nerve injury to the brachial plexus ( nerve junction that connects the spine to the upper shoulder) and when it occurs during childbirth it is appropriate to check whether the damage occurred as a result of the negligence of the obstetric team.
The injury manifests itself in weakness of the hand muscles and can reach complete paralysis of the entire arm up to full paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in removing the newborn due to the occurrence of 'shoulder 3' - an obstetric emergency that occurs when the fetus' shoulders are trapped inside the birth canal after the head has come out of the birth canal.
When should you suspect that paralysis is caused by medical malpractice?
In cases where the assessment of the weight of the fetus indicated that it is a macrosomic fetus, that is, that it is expected to be born with a weight greater than 4 weights. 5 kilograms and according to the guidelines it is better to give birth to the mother by caesarean section.
When the weight of the newborn is over 4 kilograms, a caesarean section should be considered in light of the risk factors, including gestational diabetes and the prolongation of the second stage of labor.
In the event that the medical team ignores an abnormal fetal weight assessment or other risk factors and chooses to continue with a vaginal birth and the risk of shoulder rupture and ERB paralysis is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical malpractice.
Indeed, in CA 2694/90, the Supreme Court held that "the risk that shoulder stenosis will occur during childbirth can be predicted with some degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where there is concern of its occurrence, is to conduct a caesarean section."
