A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the effect of meetings through video software on participants' creativity, compared to face-to-face meetings held in nature, compared to face-to-face meetings.
Unfortunately, it has been found that creativity does suffer in virtual meetings through screens.
The research question  led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University  was whether remote meetings using a computer preserve the creativity of office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of the distance.
The study itself began as early as 2016 but received a big boost in the two years of coronavirus, during which many employees moved to work from home.
“ People in a personal meeting move around the room, use objects and use them for creative thinking,” says Brooks.
“ In a computer session, on the other hand, the concentration on maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more video-focused when interacting, which impairs the broad and expansive idea generation process.
Space is shrinking.
To test the results of the experiment and verify whether they would repeat themselves, they were tested twice  once at Columbia University and once in real life  on engineers who knew each other from early acquaintance.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two parts  in one the subjects were asked to meet personally and develop solutions to the problem, and in the other they were asked to do so through a computer.
At the same time, 1, 490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to divide in a similar way and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking was found among those who met virtually on video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher on ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, as part of a thinking activity, people often look at their surroundings to help generate ideas, while in a video session thinking converges on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows creativity to be possible.
“ When the people are in the same room, they look around and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can evoke new associations in them.
On the other hand, research shows that relationships through a computer change our attention so that we are more focused inward and on the screen, and this reduces innovation and idea generation through looking at the environment and thinking outward.
There is no harm to critical thinking.
However, before managers run employees back to the office, the researchers note that “ working through a computer did not harm productivity itself nor people's critical thinking about innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
In other words, the damage is focused solely on creativity and not on the other forms of working with a computer."
Professor Alan Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also qualifies the findings as similar.
According to her, "there is a difference between mere creativity, such as new uses for frisbee ( one of the research questions; EG) and solutions of work."
It's also possible that when employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or when they work from home, creativity will improve."
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson also proposed future research in which such meetings would be stopped for thinking and wandering situations in the room to see how this activity would affect the final outcome.
Dr. Olson also suggested that following the study, only brainstorming sessions would allow employees to return to work, and generally suggested not to be alarmed by one study, but to conduct another investigation in the field.
"I wouldn't want workers to be forced back and not be happy, that's a bigger blow, " he says.
